  "notes": "Header title as written: 'SECTION OF No. 9 Borehole, about 300 yards west of Crook Hall, Durham.' Sheet notes: grid 'NZ 2719 4320' and 'Not on NZ 24SE'. Communicated by B.G.S. 2654 (as stamped). Date of boring or sinking 1838; borer's name written but not confidently legible (reads roughly 'Wm. G---' / 'Wm. C---'; possibly the Durham master borer 'Wm. Coulson' but NOT resolved — do not rely on it). One-inch Map 26; Six-inch Map Durham 27 NW. BGS registration NZ 24 SE 38; two pages (original PAGE NO. 7 then PAGE NO. 2, with folio '70' pencilled atop page 2). Interval numbering runs continuously across both pages (1-27 page 1, 28-57 page 2); page 2's column head carries the running depth 32-3-5 forward, matching page 1's final depth. Units are Victorian fathoms/feet/inches (1 fathom = 6 ft); BOTH the Thickness and Depth-from-Surface columns are transcribed verbatim as [fathoms, feet, inches]. Cross-check (prev depth + thickness = next depth) holds for every interval EXCEPT one CLERK SLIP at interval 28: depth written 33-3-7 where arithmetic and the following line both require 33-3-3 (see that interval's annotation). The slip does not propagate — the running total is self-consistent again from interval 29 to the base. Surface level given only approximately: 'c. 200'' O.D. No coal-seam NAMES are written anywhere in the original, and there are NO pencil seam-correlation marginalia (LM/HM/HTN/Md etc.); the filled black discs in the left margin of page 1 (beside intervals ~4 and ~14) and the blots at intervals 40 and 49 are ink spots, not lettered seam marks — hence seam_marks is empty despite 12 unnamed COAL bands being logged (thickest 4 ft 3 in at interval 8). 'Whin' (intervals 39, 51, 54, plus whin girdles in several 'post' beds) is a NE sinker's term for hard, tough, fine-grained rock distinct from 'post' (sandstone); standalone whin beds are classed 'band' to keep the hardness signal for dig-rate modelling. Final depth 85 fathoms 2 ft 4 in = 512 ft 4 in =